{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491204"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:37:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:37:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"866"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/866"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.03,0.06,0.14,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49644"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/866"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34931"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49644"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with difficulty using her fingers. She reports a 8-year history of pain in multiple hand and wrist joints bilaterally associated with swelling. She notes the pain is now impacting her daily life, particularly in her work as a receptionist, where she has worked for 10 years. She has a 25-pack-year smoking history, a history of Graves\u0027 disease and is overweight (body mass index 28kg/m^2). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"On hand examination, which of the following physical signs would most likely be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flexed distal interphalangeal joint and hyperextended proximal interphalangeal joint","Clawing of the fourth and fifth fingers with sensory deficits affecting the same digits","Fixed flexion deformity of the distal interphalangeal joint","Thenar wasting and weakness of thumb opposition, and abduction","Bony swelling of the proximal and distal interphalangeal joints"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s problems are due to\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Erheumatoid arthritis (RA). She has risk factors for RA including older age, female gender, and cigarette smoking, which is the strongest known environmental risk factor. Hand changes which may be present in advanced RA are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESwan-neck deformity: \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexion of the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint and hyperextension of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint \u003C/strong\u003E(see image below)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoutonni\u00e8re deformity: hyperextension of the DIP joint and flexion of the PIP joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EZ-deformity of the thumb: flexion and subluxation of the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joint and hyperextension of the first interphalangeal joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eother: subluxation of the MCP joints, rheumatoid nodules, and ulnar deviation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuch deformities are not common nowadays because of early treatment with disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs (e.g., methotrexate).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUlnar nerve injury\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Emay occur at the elbow or the wrist, their features are below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eelbow: sensory deficits affecting the fourth, fifth digits and ulnar aspect of the hand; weakness of the first dorsal interosseous, abductor digiti minimi, and flexor carpi ulnaris, and flexor digitorum profundus (FDP)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ewrist: sensory deficits affecting the fourth and fifth digits; weakness of the flexor pollicis brevis, adductor pollicis, interossei, third and fourth lumbricals\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClawing of the fourth and fifth fingers\u003C/strong\u003E (ulnar claw) can be seen, particularly when the injury occurs at the wrist due to the involvement of the respective lumbricals and sparing of the FDP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMallet finger deformity occurs due to extensor tendon injury of the DIP joint. It is common in ball-handling sports and presents as a \u003Cstrong\u003Efixed flexion deformity of the DIP joint\u003C/strong\u003E. In contrast, in Swan-neck deformity hyperextension of the PIP joint. There is also no history of trauma hence making the diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarpal tunnel syndrome occurs due to compression of the median nerve in the carpal tunnel, formed by the transverse carpal ligament and carpal bones. It typically presents with pain or paraesthesia over the thenar eminence and palmar surface of the thumb, second, third, and lateral half of the fourth finger. In later stages, patients may present with \u003Cstrong\u003Ethenar wasting, weakness of thumb opposition, and abduction\u003C/strong\u003E. While this is an important differential to consider given her occupation, the presence of swollen joints strongly suggests RA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOsteoarthritis is a degenerative joint disease, that typically affects larger joints (e.g. knee, hip) in an asymmetric pattern. It can result in \u003Cstrong\u003Ebony swelling of the DIP and PIP joints\u003C/strong\u003E, named Heberden and Bouchard nodes, respectively. In contrast, rheumatoid nodules most commonly present as subcutaneous nodules, typically over bony prominences or pressure areas. From the information provided in the stem, rheumatoid arthritis is more likely given the combination of the patient\u0027s age, gender, smoking history, and history of autoimmune disease. Further investigations would be required to confirm the diagnosis and differentiate osteoarthritis and other joint diseases. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Swan neck deformity is characterised by hyperflexion of the distal interphalangeal joint and hyperextension of the proximal interphalangeal joint.","Other hand changes in advanced rheumatoid arthritis are subluxation of the MCP joints, rheumatoid nodules, Boutonni\u00e8re deformity, Z-deformity of the thumb, and ulnar deviation.","Risk factors for rheumatoid arthritis include older age, female gender, and cigarette smoking."],"references":["Aletaha D, Smolen JS. Diagnosis and Management of Rheumatoid Arthritis: A Review. JAMA. 2018 Oct 2;320(13):1360\u201372.","Doughty CT, Bowley MP. Entrapment Neuropathies of the Upper Extremity. Med Clin North Am. 2019 Mar;103(2):357\u201370","Padua L, Coraci D, Erra C, Pazzaglia C, Paolasso I, Loreti C, et al. Carpal tunnel syndrome: clinical features, diagnosis, and management. The Lancet Neurology. 2016 Nov 1;15(12):1273\u201384.","Anderson D. Mallet finger - management and patient compliance. Aust Fam Physician. 2011 Feb;40(1\u20132):47\u20138.","Malfait F, Castori M, Francomano CA, Giunta C, Kosho T, Byers PH. The Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndromes. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020 Jul 30;6(1):1\u201325."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisio